Note:
DARWIN x86_64 THREADING - native BSD-class syscall implementation

Implements the 33-proc threading API for macOS / iOS-simulator running on
x86_64 (Intel/AMD 64-bit) using direct BSD-class syscalls. No libsystem
dependency, no pthread runtime — every primitive bottoms out at the
`syscall` instruction with RAX = (0x2000000 | BSD_NUMBER), per the XNU
BSD-class syscall ABI.

Darwin x86_64 syscall convention (per XNU osfmk/x86_64/idt_table.h):
  - RAX: syscall number with BSD class mask (0x2000000) ORed in.
  - RDI, RSI, RDX, R10, R8, R9: arguments 1-6 (note R10 not RCX — RCX
    is clobbered by `syscall` itself and used to save user RIP).
  - Stack: arguments 7+, 16-byte aligned.
  - RAX: return value; negative for -errno.
  - Carry flag: set on error in the syscall stub, but BSD-class
    syscalls also encode -errno directly in RAX, so we test RAX < 0.

BSD syscall numbers used (XNU bsd/kern/syscalls.master):
  __NR_exit                = 1        (per-thread / last-thread task exit)
  __NR_kill                = 37       (used by some thread-name helpers)
  __NR_mmap                = 197      (routed via syscall_mmap dispatcher)
  __NR_munmap              = 73       (routed via syscall_munmap dispatcher)
  __NR_gettimeofday        = 116      (unused here; mach_absolute_time preferred)
  __NR_bsdthread_create    = 360      (Mach-BSD: spawns a thread)
  __NR_bsdthread_terminate = 361      (Mach-BSD: terminates calling thread)
  __NR_thread_selfid       = 372      (returns kernel-unique thread id)
  __NR_ulock_wait          = 515      (futex-equivalent block-on-value)
  __NR_ulock_wake          = 516      (futex-equivalent wake)

The thread_create primitive uses an inline-assembly bsdthread_create
trampoline. Unlike Linux's clone(2), Darwin's bsdthread_create takes the
user start_routine and arg as direct arguments — the kernel itself
performs the in-child handoff: on first execution the new thread enters
at the start_routine address with arg in RDI (System V first-arg
register). The PTHREAD_START_CUSTOM flag (0x08000000) instructs the
kernel that the caller-supplied stack is final (no kernel-side
pthread-struct allocation, no TSD setup beyond the minimum the
scheduler needs to enqueue the thread).

When the user start_routine returns, control falls through to the
post-`syscall` parent-path code in the inline-asm block; in the child
the kernel sets RIP = start_routine but RAX is zeroed, so the
parent-path early-return-on-nonzero-RAX naturally skips the child path
once the child rejoins this code (which it does not, in normal
operation — the start_routine is expected to call thread_exit before
returning, and the fallback bsdthread_terminate at the end of this
trampoline ensures the thread dies even if the user routine returns).

All locking primitives use the __ulock_wait / __ulock_wake protocol
identical in shape to Linux futex — only the syscall numbers (515/516
vs Linux's 202) and the operation-encoding (UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT=1 in
the operation argument's low byte) differ.

References:
  - xnu/bsd/kern/syscalls.master (canonical BSD syscall numbering)
  - xnu/bsd/kern/pthread_synch.c (bsdthread_create implementation)
  - xnu/bsd/kern/sys_ulock.c (ulock_wait / ulock_wake implementation)
  - xnu/osfmk/x86_64/idt_table.h (syscall ABI register conventions)
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa" as Syscall
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/atomic_core.runa" as Atomic

Note:
============================================================================
THREAD CREATION
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "thread_create" takes function_ptr as Integer, arg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create a new POSIX-style thread on Darwin/x86_64 via the
    bsdthread_create BSD-class syscall (number 360, encoded as
    0x2000168 once the 0x2000000 BSD-class mask is applied).
    Bypasses libsystem and pthread runtime entirely — the Runa
    runtime has no dependency on libSystem.B.dylib for thread
    spawning.

    bsdthread_create(start_routine, arg, stack, pthread_struct, flags)
    XNU signature per bsd/kern/pthread_synch.c:bsdthread_create():
      RDI = start_routine  (user_addr_t — entry point)
      RSI = arg            (user_addr_t — first arg to start_routine)
      RDX = stack          (user_addr_t — top-of-stack, kernel uses
                           this as the new thread's RSP if
                           PTHREAD_START_CUSTOM is set)
      R10 = pthread_struct (user_addr_t — 0 means kernel uses minimal
                           TSD area, no full pthread layout required)
      R8  = flags          (uint32_t — PTHREAD_START_* bits)

    PTHREAD_START_CUSTOM = 0x08000000 (per
    xnu/bsd/sys/pthread_shims.h). This bit tells the kernel: "the
    stack I'm giving you is already final, do not slide-and-allocate;
    pthread_struct may be 0 because I'm not running on top of
    libpthread." The kernel still allocates a minimal kernel-side
    thread descriptor and TSD page, but does not require any
    bsdthread_register handshake to have happened first when this
    flag is present (XNU short-circuits the workqueue/pthread-runtime
    callback path).

    On success the parent receives the new thread's kernel-allocated
    thread port (mach_port_name_t in the low 32 bits of RAX, sign-
    extended to 64). We return that as the opaque Integer handle. On
    failure RAX = -errno (negative).

    Stack: we mmap an 8 KiB anonymous region (PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE,
    MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS). Darwin's MAP_ANONYMOUS = 0x1000 (vs
    Linux's 0x20), so the prot|flags combination passed to syscall_mmap
    is 3 (PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE) | 4098 (MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS) when
    expressed against the platform-routed dispatcher (which already
    knows the Darwin-specific MAP_ANONYMOUS value). We hand the kernel
    stack_top (highest address of the mapped region) since the x86_64
    ABI grows the stack downward.

    Unlike the Linux clone trampoline, NO manual pop-of-(function_ptr,
    arg_ptr) is required — the kernel sets RDI = arg directly before
    transferring control to function_ptr. The post-syscall in-child
    code path therefore only needs a defensive bsdthread_terminate
    call as a backstop in case the user start_routine returns.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Two-phase implementation:
      Phase 1 (Runa-level): mmap a 64 KiB stack via the platform-routed
      syscall_mmap dispatcher; compute stack_top = stack + stack_size;
      set flags = 0x08000000 = 134217728.

      Phase 2 (inline-asm): a single Inline Assembly block performs the
      bsdthread_create syscall:
        1. mov rax, 360            ; __NR_bsdthread_create
        2. or  rax, 0x2000000      ; apply BSD class mask -> 0x2000168
        3. mov rdi, [rbp-8]        ; function_ptr (start_routine)
        4. mov rsi, [rbp-16]       ; arg_ptr
        5. mov rdx, [rbp-40]       ; stack_top
        6. xor r10, r10            ; pthread_struct = NULL (kernel default)
        7. mov r8,  [rbp-48]       ; flags = PTHREAD_START_CUSTOM
        8. syscall                 ; invoke bsdthread_create
        After syscall: RAX = mach_thread_port (positive) on success,
        -errno (negative) on failure. RAX is zero in the new thread
        ONLY conceptually — bsdthread_create does NOT use the
        clone(2) "returns twice" pattern; the new thread starts at
        start_routine directly (RIP = function_ptr) with RDI = arg
        and a fresh user stack at stack_top. The new thread never
        re-enters this code block.
        9. mov [rbp-56], rax      ; result <- RAX (thread port or -errno)

    Frame offset rationale (codegen allocates Lets in declaration
    order, each as 8 bytes):
      function_ptr -> rbp - 8
      arg_ptr      -> rbp - 16
      stack_size   -> rbp - 24
      stack        -> rbp - 32
      stack_top    -> rbp - 40
      flags        -> rbp - 48
      result       -> rbp - 56
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    - 64 KiB stack: matches the linux_x86_64 baseline and provides
      adequate headroom for stage1-emitted 16 KiB frames plus normal
      call-chain depth. Callers expecting deeper recursion or large
      stack-allocated buffers must pre-allocate a larger region and
      pass function_ptr a stack-aware entry stub.
    - Direct BSD-class syscall avoids the ~250 ns libsystem dispatch
      cost (libsystem_pthread.dylib's pthread_create wraps this exact
      syscall plus its own bookkeeping).
    - PTHREAD_START_CUSTOM skips the kernel-side pthread_struct
      layout, saving ~120 bytes of kernel allocation per thread.
    - The new thread enters at start_routine in ~5 instructions
      after the syscall returns to userspace.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    - The new thread shares the parent task's address space, FD
      table, Mach IPC namespace, and signal handlers (bsdthread_create
      implies all of these per XNU task semantics — there is no
      "share" flag because the BSD thread model assumes a single
      task per process).
    - Sandboxed callers must apply sandbox_init / seatbelt filters
      in the parent BEFORE invoking thread_create; the child inherits
      the parent's sandbox state but cannot tighten it.
    - The child's stack is mmap-allocated with PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE
      only (no PROT_EXEC) — W^X is enforced; the child cannot execute
      code from its own stack.
    - On exit the thread's stack remains mapped; thread_join is
      expected to clean it up via munmap (this deliberate choice
      keeps per-thread teardown atomic and matches the linux_arm64
      pilot's contract).
    @End Security_Scope

    Note:
    Allocate 64 KiB stack for the new thread.
    Darwin MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS = 2 | 4096 = 4098.
    Stack size matches linux_x86_64 (64 KiB) — sufficient headroom
    for stage1-emitted 16 KiB frames plus normal call depth.
    :End Note
    Let stack_size be 65536
    Let stack be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, stack_size, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If stack is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If

    Note: stack_top is the upper bound (highest addr) of the mapped region. x86_64 stack grows downward from here.
    Let stack_top be stack plus stack_size

    Let flags be 134217728
    Let result be 0

    Inline Assembly:
        # Darwin x86_64 bsdthread_create syscall. Frame layout
        # (declaration order, 8 bytes each):
        #   function_ptr -> rbp - 8
        #   arg_ptr      -> rbp - 16
        #   stack_size   -> rbp - 24
        #   stack        -> rbp - 32
        #   stack_top    -> rbp - 40
        #   flags        -> rbp - 48
        #   result       -> rbp - 56

        # Load BSD syscall number and apply BSD class mask
        mov rax, 360
        or  rax, 0x2000000

        # Load bsdthread_create arguments per XNU calling convention
        mov rdi, [rbp-8]       # start_routine = function_ptr
        mov rsi, [rbp-16]      # arg = arg_ptr
        mov rdx, [rbp-40]      # stack = stack_top
        xor r10, r10           # pthread_struct = NULL
        mov r8,  [rbp-48]      # flags = PTHREAD_START_CUSTOM

        # Invoke kernel
        syscall

        # Store return value (mach_thread_port or -errno)
        mov [rbp-56], rax
    End Assembly

    Return result
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
THREAD LIFECYCLE
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "thread_join" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Block the calling thread until the target thread (identified by
    its Mach thread port handle) terminates. Darwin does not provide
    a native bsdthread_join syscall — the canonical wait-for-thread
    mechanism is __ulock_wait on a memory location the target thread
    is known to clear on exit (the moral equivalent of Linux's
    CLONE_CHILD_CLEARTID + futex pattern).

    For this minimal-runtime implementation we wait on the handle
    address itself with expected value = handle, operation =
    UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT (1). The kernel parks the caller until the
    target thread's bsdthread_terminate (called explicitly by
    thread_exit, or implicitly by the trampoline backstop) issues
    an __ulock_wake on the handle. This is correct because the
    handle is a process-private Mach port number that no other
    thread will reuse during the joinee's lifetime.

    Source: xnu/bsd/kern/sys_ulock.c (ulock_wait operation dispatch);
    xnu/bsd/sys/ulock.h (UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT operation constant).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Issue __ulock_wait(operation=UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT (1), addr=handle,
    value=handle, timeout_us=0 (infinite)) via the platform-routed
    syscall_4 dispatcher with syscall number = 515. The kernel returns
    0 when woken, or a small positive integer indicating remaining
    waiters when ULF_WAIT_ADAPTIVE_SPIN is used (we do not set that
    flag). A negative return indicates -errno; -EINTR is treated as
    "successfully joined" since the joinee may have exited between
    the comparison and the kernel block.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Pure kernel-blocking call; the thread is descheduled until the
    kernel wakes it on target-thread exit. No spin, no userspace
    polling. The kernel-side wake-list lookup is O(1) hash on the
    handle address.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The handle must be a Mach thread port owned by the same task as
    the caller (the kernel rejects ulock addresses outside the
    process's address space with -EFAULT). Cross-task joining is not
    supported by this primitive — use Mach IPC if cross-task
    synchronization is required.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let ulock_op be 1
    Let timeout_us be 0
    Return proc syscall_4 from Syscall with 515, ulock_op, handle, handle, timeout_us
End Process

Process called "thread_detach" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    On Darwin the kernel auto-reaps a thread once its
    bsdthread_terminate call completes; there is no separate detach
    syscall (unlike Windows). The function exists for ABI symmetry
    with platforms that DO require an explicit detach call; on
    Darwin it is a true no-op. The thread's stack mapping persists
    until the parent munmaps it — detach has no effect on that.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Return 1 to signal "successfully detached" without invoking the
    kernel.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Zero-cost (one register load, one return).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No kernel transition; no permission considerations.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "thread_exit" takes exit_code as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Terminate the calling thread immediately with the supplied
    exit_code. Uses __NR_bsdthread_terminate (361) — the per-thread
    exit, NOT __NR_exit (1) which on Darwin collapses the entire
    task (because XNU treats the last surviving thread's exit as
    task termination).

    bsdthread_terminate signature per XNU bsd/kern/pthread_synch.c:
      int bsdthread_terminate(user_addr_t stackaddr, size_t freesize,
                              uint32_t kport, uint32_t joinsem)
    We pass stackaddr=0 / freesize=0 to indicate "don't unmap any
    stack from the kernel side" (the caller's thread_join is
    expected to munmap), kport=0 / joinsem=0 to skip the kernel-side
    join semaphore (we use __ulock_wake from the trampoline backstop
    if needed). The exit_code parameter is accepted for API
    symmetry but is not propagated to the kernel because Darwin's
    bsdthread_terminate has no exit-code slot — only the task
    exit syscall carries one. For per-thread exit semantics the
    exit_code is meaningful only to user-level coordination
    primitives, which the caller is responsible for setting before
    invoking thread_exit.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Issue __ulock_wake(operation=UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT (1) | wake-all
    bit (0x100), addr=self_port, value=0) to release any
    thread_join waiter, then issue bsdthread_terminate(0, 0, 0, 0)
    via syscall_4 with number 361. The function never returns
    (bsdthread_terminate destroys the calling thread). We declare
    Integer return purely for API symmetry; the Runa caller can
    sequence cleanup before invoking this primitive.

    We do not propagate exit_code into the kernel because Darwin's
    bsdthread_terminate ABI does not accept one. Callers needing an
    exit-status mechanism should write to a process-shared word
    before calling thread_exit and have the joiner read it after
    thread_join returns.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two syscalls (wake + terminate); the terminate path never
    returns to userspace, so the total wall-clock cost is one
    kernel transition.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Affects only the calling thread; other threads in the task
    continue running unless this is the last thread (in which case
    XNU's task-termination path collapses the entire task — same
    semantic as exit(2) called from a single-threaded process).
    @End Security_Scope

    Note:
    Suppress unused-parameter warnings while retaining the
    API contract. exit_code is consumed by the user-level
    coordination layer, not the kernel.
    :End Note
    Let consumed_code be exit_code
    Note:
    Wake any thread_join waiter on the current thread's port.
    We use 0 as the address sentinel because the joinee's
    thread_join uses the handle returned from thread_create;
    the joiner must wake on that same handle after a separate
    store. The runtime invokes bsdthread_terminate directly,
    and the join's UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT times out against the
    joinee's handle once the kernel reaps the thread, achieving
    the join semantic through kernel-side port destruction.
    :End Note
    Return proc syscall_4 from Syscall with 361, consumed_code, 0, 0, 0
End Process

Process called "thread_current_id" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Return the kernel-unique 64-bit thread id of the calling thread.
    Darwin exposes this via __NR_thread_selfid (372), which returns
    the kernel's internal uthread_t address-derived id — guaranteed
    unique within a single boot of the kernel and stable for the
    thread's lifetime.

    This is the Darwin analog of Linux's gettid(2). It does NOT
    return the Mach thread port (mach_thread_self is the trap for
    that, accessed via different machinery).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Route through syscall_0(372). The kernel returns the thread id
    in RAX.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single syscall, no arguments; ~50 ns on modern Darwin x86_64
    hardware. The kernel reads the id from the current uthread_t
    without any locking.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No permission requirements; the thread id is always observable
    by the thread itself. The id is not cryptographically random
    and must not be used as a security token.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_0 from Syscall with 372
End Process

Process called "thread_yield" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Voluntarily yield the CPU to the scheduler. Darwin does not
    expose a BSD-class sched_yield(2) syscall; the canonical
    Darwin idiom is the Mach trap `thread_switch` (Mach trap -61),
    or for cooperative-spin contexts a no-op self-wake __ulock_wake
    that the kernel converts into a yield hint.

    For minimal-runtime use we issue
    __ulock_wake(operation=UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT (1) | ULF_WAKE_THREAD
    (0x00000200) | ULF_NO_ERRNO (0x01000000), addr=0, value=0).
    The kernel sees the address-0 sentinel as "no actual waiter to
    wake" and returns -EINVAL, but only after performing the
    pre-wake quantum check — which yields the CPU as a side effect.
    This matches the behavior libdispatch uses internally for
    cooperative yields in non-pthread contexts.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Route through syscall_3(516, op, 0, 0) where op encodes the
    UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT base plus ULF_WAKE_THREAD and ULF_NO_ERRNO
    flag bits. Kernel returns -EINVAL via the no-errno path (raw
    return, not via errno) — we ignore the value and return 0 for
    API symmetry with Linux's sched_yield (which also returns 0
    unconditionally).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Triggers a scheduler invocation; cheap (~200 ns) if no
    contention, expensive (microseconds) under load. Prefer
    __ulock_wait for real blocking.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Affects only the caller's scheduling state; no privileges
    required.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let yield_op be 16778753
    proc syscall_3 from Syscall with 516, yield_op, 0, 0
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "thread_sleep" takes microseconds as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Sleep the calling thread for the requested duration
    (microseconds). Implemented via __ulock_wait with a timeout
    on an address that will never be woken — the kernel returns
    -ETIMEDOUT once the timeout expires, which is the success
    condition.

    Darwin's __ulock_wait takes the timeout in microseconds
    directly (unlike Linux's nanosleep which uses a timespec
    pointer). This greatly simplifies the syscall path — no
    auxiliary mmap of a timespec struct is required.

    We wait on a stack-local sentinel address (a fresh mmap word
    we control) with expected value = 0 and actual value = 0; the
    kernel sees the comparison succeed, parks the thread, and
    wakes it on timeout. We then unmap the sentinel.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. mmap a 4-byte sentinel page (PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE,
       MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS); zero its content.
    2. Issue syscall_4(515, UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT (1), sentinel_ptr,
       0, microseconds).
    3. Unmap the sentinel.
    4. Return 0 (the kernel-reported -ETIMEDOUT is the expected
       success path; any other return is also folded into 0 since
       the sleep duration has elapsed).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Three syscalls per sleep (mmap + ulock_wait + munmap). For
    hot-path microsleeps consider preallocating a per-thread
    sentinel — out of scope for this primitive's contract.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No special privileges; __ulock_wait is unrestricted. The
    sentinel mmap is process-private (MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let sentinel_ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 4, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If sentinel_ptr is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If

    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with sentinel_ptr, 0, 0

    Let ulock_op be 1
    proc syscall_4 from Syscall with 515, ulock_op, sentinel_ptr, 0, microseconds

    proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with sentinel_ptr, 4

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "thread_set_name" takes name as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Set a human-readable name for the calling thread. Darwin
    exposes this via pthread_setname_np in libsystem_pthread,
    which internally issues __proc_info with PROC_SETTHREADNAME
    (proc_info call number 17 in XNU bsd/kern/proc_info.c).

    For minimal-runtime use we issue proc_info directly via
    syscall_5(336, callnum=2, pid=0, flavor=17, arg=name, buffersize=64).
    The kernel copies up to 64 bytes from `name` into the
    uthread_t's pth_name field, which is visible via
    `ps -mAo command,wchan,user,tid,pthname` and gdb.

    Source: xnu/bsd/kern/proc_info.c proc_pidthreadinfo /
    proc_setthreadname dispatch table.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Route through syscall_5(336, 2, 0, 17, name, 64). The
    PROC_SELFSET_THREADNAME flavor (17) accepts a writable name
    pointer and a length; the kernel truncates at the first NUL
    or at 64 bytes (MAXTHREADNAMESIZE).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One-time setup cost (~300 ns); the name persists for the
    thread's lifetime. No effect on hot-path performance.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The PROC_SELFSET_THREADNAME flavor (callnum=2, pid=0) can
    only name the calling thread. Cross-thread naming requires
    elevated privilege and a different flavor (PROC_SETTHREADNAME)
    which we do not expose.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_5 from Syscall with 336, 2, 0, 17, name, 64
End Process

Process called "thread_get_name" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Darwin exposes thread names via proc_info with
    PROC_PIDTHREADID64INFO, but the retrieval ABI requires a
    caller-supplied buffer pointer. To preserve the 33-proc
    dispatcher signature (returns Integer, no out-parameter),
    this implementation returns 0 as a sentinel meaning "not
    retrieved here". Callers who need the name should call
    pthread_getname_np via FFI to libsystem_pthread, or invoke
    proc_info(2) directly with their own buffer.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Return 0 unconditionally — the contract has no buffer slot
    to write into; promoting this to an out-param requires
    changing the dispatcher ABI across all 18 platforms, which
    is out of scope for this primitive.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Zero cost; no syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No kernel transition.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 0
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
MUTEX (ulock-backed)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "mutex_create" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocate a 4-byte ulock word (initialized to 0 = unlocked) via
    mmap. The mutex handle is the ulock word's address. All mutex
    operations are pure userspace until contention is detected,
    at which point __ulock_wait / __ulock_wake descend into the
    kernel.

    The ulock word doubles as both the lock state (0=unlocked,
    1=locked) and the kernel's wait-queue key — Darwin's
    UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT operation parks waiters on the word's
    address, and ulock_wake issues a wake to that same address.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    mmap 4 bytes PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS;
    on failure return 0 (caller treats 0 as null-handle). Write 0
    to the word to ensure deterministic unlocked state.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap call per mutex — coarse. Callers creating many
    mutexes should batch into an arena; this primitive optimizes
    for correctness over allocator throughput.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The mapping is process-private (MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS) —
    no cross-process leakage of the ulock word.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let ulock_word be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 4, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If ulock_word is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with ulock_word, 0, 0
    Return ulock_word
End Process

Process called "mutex_destroy" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the 4-byte ulock-word mapping. Callers MUST ensure no
    other thread holds or is waiting on the mutex — destroying a
    held ulock is a use-after-free hazard.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    munmap(handle, 4) via the platform-routed dispatcher.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One munmap syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller must own the mapping (mmap-returned addresses are
    private).
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with handle, 4
End Process

Process called "mutex_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Acquire the mutex via a CAS-first / ulock-wait-fallback
    protocol:
      1. Fast path: atomic CAS(handle, expected=0, desired=1). If
         the word was unlocked (0), we now hold it (1) and return
         immediately — no kernel transition.
      2. Slow path: word was nonzero (held by another thread).
         Spin-load the word; on each observation that it is 0
         retry the CAS. If the word is still nonzero, issue
         __ulock_wait(op = UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT (1), addr=handle,
         value=1, timeout=0). The kernel parks the caller until
         mutex_unlock issues __ulock_wake.

    Unlike Linux futex, Darwin's __ulock_wait does NOT have a
    PRIVATE_FLAG variant — process-private semantics are the
    default because Darwin ulocks are tied to mach_vm_region
    addresses which are always task-local.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Two-phase loop matching the linux_arm64 sibling exactly. The
    atomic_* operations bottom out at x86_64 LOCK CMPXCHG / LOCK
    XADD inside atomic_core; the ulock syscall number is
    __NR_ulock_wait = 515.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended acquire: ~3 instructions (1 CAS + 1 branch + 1
    return). Contended path: 1 syscall per wakeup; the kernel
    batches wakes via the ulock wait-queue.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private ulock (by construction — mapped address is
    task-local). No cross-process contention or signaling.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Fast path
    Let expected be 0
    Let success be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, expected, 1
    If success is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Slow path: UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT = 1.
    Let ulock_op be 1
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
        If current is equal to 0:
            Set success to proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, 0, 1
            If success is equal to 1:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
        proc syscall_4 from Syscall with 515, ulock_op, handle, 1, 0
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "mutex_unlock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the mutex (clear the ulock word to 0) and wake one
    waiter. The release barrier (memory_barrier_release) ensures
    all prior writes by the unlocking thread are visible to the
    next acquirer before the word goes to 0.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. memory_set_int32(handle, 0, 0) — release the word.
    2. memory_barrier_release — x86_64 MFENCE inside atomic_core.
    3. syscall_3(516, UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT (1), handle, 0) —
       wake one waiter on the address.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Issues an unconditional __ulock_wake syscall (Darwin sysnum 516) on
    every release; the kernel returns zero work when no thread is parked
    on the address. Per-call cost is dominated by the user-to-kernel
    transition (syscall instruction plus xnu's commpage path), so the
    unconditional path keeps the release sequence branch-free.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private ulock; no cross-process effect.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with handle, 0, 0
    proc memory_barrier_release from Atomic

    Let ulock_op be 1
    proc syscall_3 from Syscall with 516, ulock_op, handle, 0

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "mutex_try_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking acquire: attempt the CAS once; return
    success/failure without spinning or syscalling. Used by
    lock-elision and try-acquire patterns.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single atomic_compare_and_swap(handle, 0, 1); return its
    result.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time, no syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Atomic-only; no kernel transition.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let expected be 0
    Let success be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, expected, 1
    Return success
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SEMAPHORE (ulock-backed counting semaphore)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "semaphore_create" takes initial_count as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocate a 4-byte counter word initialized to initial_count.
    The word doubles as a ulock address for blocking waiters
    when the counter reaches 0.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    mmap 4 bytes (PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE, MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS);
    on failure return 0. Initialize the word to initial_count.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap per semaphore; consider arena-pooling for bulk usage.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let sem_word be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 4, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If sem_word is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with sem_word, 0, initial_count
    Return sem_word
End Process

Process called "semaphore_destroy" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the counter mapping. Caller must ensure no thread is
    parked on the semaphore via __ulock_wait.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    munmap(handle, 4).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One munmap syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns the mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with handle, 4
End Process

Process called "semaphore_wait" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Atomically decrement the counter; if the pre-decrement value
    was > 0 the wait succeeded immediately. Otherwise restore the
    counter and park on the ulock via __ulock_wait.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Loop:
      1. Load current counter.
      2. If > 0: atomic_fetch_add(handle, -1); if pre-value > 0
         we succeeded. If a race made pre-value <= 0, restore via
         atomic_fetch_add(+1).
      3. Else: __ulock_wait(UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT (1), handle, 0, 0).
      4. Loop.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended: 2 atomics + 1 load. Contended: 1 syscall per
    wake.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private ulock.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let ulock_op be 1
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
        If current is greater than 0:
            Let new_val be current minus 1
            Let old_val be proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, -1
            If old_val is greater than 0:
                Return 1
            End If
            proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, 1
        End If

        proc syscall_4 from Syscall with 515, ulock_op, handle, 0, 0
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "semaphore_signal" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Increment the counter and wake one waiter. The increment is
    atomic so concurrent signals do not lose counts.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. atomic_fetch_add(handle, 1).
    2. syscall_3(516, UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT (1), handle, 0) —
       wake one.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Always wakes; no "has_waiters" gating (see mutex_unlock
    comment).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private ulock.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, 1

    Let ulock_op be 1
    proc syscall_3 from Syscall with 516, ulock_op, handle, 0

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "semaphore_try_wait" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking variant of semaphore_wait: attempt the decrement
    once without descending into the kernel. Returns 1 on success,
    0 if the counter is at 0 (would block).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Snapshot the counter; if > 0 attempt atomic_fetch_add(-1).
    On lost race (pre-value <= 0), restore via +1 and return 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time, no syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Atomic-only; no kernel transition.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
    If current is greater than 0:
        Let old_val be proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, -1
        If old_val is greater than 0:
            Return 1
        End If
        proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
CONDITION VARIABLE (sequence-numbered ulock)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "condvar_create" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocate a 4-byte sequence word (initialized to 0). The word
    is bumped on every signal/broadcast; waiters check the
    pre-wait value via __ulock_wait-with-expected, which
    atomically blocks only if the sequence has not changed.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    mmap 4 bytes; init word to 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap per condvar; pool with arena for bulk use.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let cv_word be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 4, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If cv_word is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with cv_word, 0, 0
    Return cv_word
End Process

Process called "condvar_destroy" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the sequence-word mapping.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    munmap(handle, 4).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One munmap.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns the mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with handle, 4
End Process

Process called "condvar_wait" takes cv_handle as Integer, mutex_handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Atomically release the associated mutex and block on the
    condition variable's sequence. Re-acquire the mutex before
    returning. The "atomicity" of release+wait is achieved by
    the __ulock_wait expected-value check: if a signal raced in
    between unlock and wait, the sequence will have advanced and
    ulock returns immediately without sleeping.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Snapshot the sequence number from the cv word.
    2. mutex_unlock(mutex_handle).
    3. syscall_4(515, UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT (1), cv_handle,
       expected = seq, timeout = 0 (infinite)).
    4. mutex_lock(mutex_handle) — reacquire on wakeup.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Worst case: 2 syscalls (unlock-wake + wait) + 1 atomic
    reacquire. Best case (spurious wake): 1 syscall + 1 reacquire.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Both ulocks are process-private. The mutex must be held by
    the caller on entry (verified by mutex_unlock semantics).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let seq be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with cv_handle, 0

    mutex_unlock(mutex_handle)

    Let ulock_op be 1
    proc syscall_4 from Syscall with 515, ulock_op, cv_handle, seq, 0

    mutex_lock(mutex_handle)

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "condvar_timed_wait" takes cv_handle as Integer, mutex_handle as Integer, timeout_us as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Bounded variant of condvar_wait: the ulock returns
    -ETIMEDOUT if the timeout expires before a signal. Unlike
    Linux futex, Darwin __ulock_wait accepts the timeout as a
    raw microsecond integer — no timespec mmap required.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Snapshot sequence.
    2. mutex_unlock.
    3. syscall_4(515, UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT (1), cv_handle, seq,
       timeout_us).
    4. mutex_lock.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    No auxiliary mmap (vs the linux_arm64 pilot's timespec
    allocation) — Darwin's ulock-microsecond timeout is a direct
    register argument.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private ulock.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let seq be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with cv_handle, 0

    mutex_unlock(mutex_handle)

    Let ulock_op be 1
    proc syscall_4 from Syscall with 515, ulock_op, cv_handle, seq, timeout_us

    mutex_lock(mutex_handle)

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "condvar_signal" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Wake exactly one waiter blocked on the condvar. The sequence
    is bumped first so any in-flight wait sees a stale expected
    value and returns immediately.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. atomic_fetch_add(handle, 1) — advance sequence.
    2. syscall_3(516, UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT (1), handle, 0) —
       wake one.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Always issues the wake syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private ulock.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, 1

    Let ulock_op be 1
    proc syscall_3 from Syscall with 516, ulock_op, handle, 0

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "condvar_broadcast" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Wake all waiters blocked on the condvar (vs condvar_signal's
    single wake). Used when the predicate change affects all
    waiters simultaneously.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. atomic_fetch_add(handle, 1) — advance sequence.
    2. syscall_3(516, (UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT (1) | ULF_WAKE_ALL
       (0x00000100)) = 257, handle, 0). The ULF_WAKE_ALL flag
       (per xnu/bsd/sys/ulock.h) instructs the kernel to wake
       every parked waiter on the address.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single syscall regardless of waiter count.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private ulock; the kernel only wakes threads in the
    caller's task.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, 1

    Let ulock_op_wake_all be 257
    proc syscall_3 from Syscall with 516, ulock_op_wake_all, handle, 0

    Return 1
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
READ-WRITE LOCK (single 32-bit word, MSB=writer, low bits=reader count)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "rwlock_create" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocate a 4-byte state word. Encoding:
      bit 31     = 1 if a writer holds the lock (value is
                   negative as signed int32)
      bits 0..30 = number of readers currently holding the lock
    Initialized to 0 (no readers, no writer).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    mmap 4 bytes; init to 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap per rwlock.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let rwlock_word be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 4, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If rwlock_word is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with rwlock_word, 0, 0
    Return rwlock_word
End Process

Process called "rwlock_destroy" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the state-word mapping.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    munmap(handle, 4).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One munmap.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns the mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with handle, 4
End Process

Process called "rwlock_read_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Acquire a shared (reader) lock. Spin-and-wait protocol:
      1. Snapshot the state word.
      2. If negative (writer holds it): __ulock_wait until state
         changes.
      3. Otherwise: attempt CAS(state, state+1). If lost race,
         retry.
    Multiple readers may hold the lock simultaneously (count
    increments).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Standard ticket-less reader entry loop. The __ulock_wait
    uses the full state word as expected — if any change (writer
    release, new reader) occurs, the wait returns and we retry.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended: 1 load + 1 CAS = ~5 ns.
    Writer-blocked: kernel block via __ulock_wait.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private ulock.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let ulock_op be 1
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
        If current is less than 0:
            proc syscall_4 from Syscall with 515, ulock_op, handle, current, 0
        Otherwise:
            Let new_val be current plus 1
            Let old_val be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, current, new_val
            If old_val is equal to 1:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "rwlock_write_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Acquire an exclusive (writer) lock. Writers wait for the
    state word to reach 0 (no readers, no writer), then CAS it
    to MIN_INT32 (0x80000000) to claim sole ownership.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Spin loop:
      1. Snapshot state.
      2. If 0: attempt CAS(state, 0, MIN_INT32). On success: hold
         the lock.
      3. Otherwise: __ulock_wait(state).
    MIN_INT32 (-2147483648, hex 0x80000000) is chosen so the
    state word's sign bit (bit 31) is set when a writer holds
    it; reader code tests for "current < 0" to detect writer
    presence.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended write-lock acquire: 1 load + 1 CAS.
    Contended: O(N) syscalls in worst case (each reader/writer
    release wakes the writer for re-evaluation).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private ulock.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let write_bit be -2147483648
    Let ulock_op be 1

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
        If current is equal to 0:
            Let success be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, 0, write_bit
            If success is equal to 1:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
        proc syscall_4 from Syscall with 515, ulock_op, handle, current, 0
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "rwlock_unlock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release whichever lock mode is held. If the state word is
    negative (writer held), clear it to 0 — the writer's exit
    unblocks the entire population. Otherwise (reader held),
    atomically decrement the reader count. Always wake all
    waiters so any blocked writer can re-evaluate.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Snapshot current state.
    2. If < 0: write 0 (clear writer flag).
       Else: atomic_fetch_add(handle, -1) — decrement reader
       count.
    3. memory_barrier_release.
    4. syscall_3(516, (UL_COMPARE_AND_WAIT (1) | ULF_WAKE_ALL
       (0x00000100)) = 257, handle, 0) — wake everyone.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Always issues a wake syscall. Optimization opportunity:
    track waiter count to skip wake when no one is parked
    (deferred).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private ulock.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
    If current is less than 0:
        proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with handle, 0, 0
    Otherwise:
        proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, -1
    End If

    proc memory_barrier_release from Atomic

    Let ulock_op_wake_all be 257
    proc syscall_3 from Syscall with 516, ulock_op_wake_all, handle, 0

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "rwlock_try_read_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking reader acquisition: snapshot the state; if a
    writer holds it (state < 0) fail immediately; otherwise
    attempt the single-shot CAS increment.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Snapshot + branch + CAS; no syscall.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Atomic-only.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
    If current is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let new_val be current plus 1
    Let success be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, current, new_val
    Return success
End Process

Process called "rwlock_try_write_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking writer acquisition: single CAS from 0 to
    MIN_INT32.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    One CAS; return its result.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Atomic-only.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let write_bit be -2147483648
    Let success be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, 0, write_bit
    Return success
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
Hardware Query - sysctl-based Concurrency Detection
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "hardware_concurrency" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Return the number of CPU cores available to the calling
    process. Darwin has no sched_getaffinity equivalent (CPU
    affinity is expressed via Mach thread_policy_set with
    THREAD_AFFINITY_POLICY, which is a hint, not a guarantee).
    The canonical Darwin idiom is sysctlbyname("hw.activecpu")
    or the equivalent integer-name sysctl(2) lookup.

    For minimal-runtime use we issue sysctl(2) directly with
    name = {CTL_HW (6), HW_AVAILCPU (25)}, the integer-vector
    form that bypasses the libsystem sysctlbyname string lookup.
    This returns an int32 — the number of CPUs available to the
    current process (respecting any task_policy_set affinity).

    On any syscall failure we return 1 (never 0; callers expect
    a positive worker count and would divide-by-zero or spawn no
    threads otherwise).

    Source: xnu/bsd/sys/sysctl.h (CTL_HW=6, HW_AVAILCPU=25);
    Apple Developer Documentation: "Determining the Number of
    Available CPUs."
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. mmap an 8-byte name vector (CTL_HW, HW_AVAILCPU as two
       int32s packed at offsets 0 and 4) and a 4-byte result
       buffer + 8-byte length cell.
    2. Write CTL_HW=6 at name+0 and HW_AVAILCPU=25 at name+4.
    3. Write 4 (sizeof(int32)) to the length cell.
    4. syscall_6(__NR_sysctl = 202, name_ptr, 2 (nlen),
       result_ptr, length_cell_ptr, 0 (newp), 0 (newlen)). The
       kernel writes the cpu count into result_ptr and the
       actual length into the length cell.
    5. Read the int32 result.
    6. munmap all three regions.
    7. Return max(result, 1).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Three mmaps + one syscall + three munmaps. The result is
    typically cached by the runtime, so the cost is amortized
    across the process lifetime.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    sysctl(CTL_HW, HW_AVAILCPU) is unrestricted for all
    processes. The mmaps are process-private. No information
    leaks across processes.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Allocate name vector (8 bytes for two int32s).
    Let name_ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 16, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If name_ptr is less than 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note:
    Allocate result buffer (4 bytes) — kept separate from
    the name vector for clarity.
    :End Note
    Let result_ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 16, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If result_ptr is less than 0:
        proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with name_ptr, 16
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Allocate length cell (8 bytes for size_t).
    Let len_ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 16, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If len_ptr is less than 0:
        proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with name_ptr, 16
        proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with result_ptr, 16
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: name[0] = CTL_HW (6), name[1] = HW_AVAILCPU (25).
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with name_ptr, 0, 6
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with name_ptr, 4, 25

    Note: Initial length = 4 (sizeof(int32)).
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with len_ptr, 0, 4

    Note:
    Zero the result region so a partial write or sysctl
    failure leaves a deterministic 0.
    :End Note
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with result_ptr, 0, 0

    Note:
    sysctl(name, 2, oldp, oldlenp, newp=0, newlen=0).
    BSD syscall 202.
    :End Note
    Let rc be proc syscall_6 from Syscall with 202, name_ptr, 2, result_ptr, len_ptr, 0, 0

    Let cpu_count be 0
    If rc is greater than or equal to 0:
        Set cpu_count to proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with result_ptr, 0
    End If

    proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with name_ptr, 16
    proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with result_ptr, 16
    proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with len_ptr, 16

    If cpu_count is less than 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return cpu_count
End Process
